<P>
<DIV ALIGN=center>
    <b>Homework Assignment 4: Creating Diamonds with doubly nested Loops</b><BR>
</DIV>
<P>
<HR>
Use your solution to
<a href="http://web.stcloudstate.edu/aanda/cs200/labs/lab10f10.html">Lab 10</a> to use doubly nested loops to create a diamond shape.<br>
<HR>
<P>
Create a Webpage with the following elements:
<ol type=I>
    <li> Standard identifying information.
    <ol>
	<li> The file name will be <tt>Diamonds.html</tt> in your CS200 directory.
	<li> The title (what's displayed on the top bar of the browser window)
	     will include:
	 <ul>
	     <li>Your name
	     <li>the course
	     <li>the assignment &amp; number
	     <li>the date
	 </ul>
	 <li> Centered at the top of the Webpage will be the same information
	     that is in the title.
    </ol>
    <li> Provide a documented <u>textbox</u> for the user to enter a size indicating the number of asterisks to use on a side for the ASCII-art diamonds.<br>
    [<b>note:</b> the height and width will be twice that, minus one]</li>
    <li> Ensure that the minimum size will be two.<br>
         Else, display a message, and let the user re-enter.</li>
    <li> Print two diamonds on successive sets of lines.
    <ol>
	<li>the first will be solid asterisks.
	<li>the second will be an outline of asterisks only.
    </ol>
</ol>
<P>
<HR>
<h4>For Example:</h4>
For a size of 4:

<pre>

   *   
  ***  
 ***** 
*******
 ***** 
  ***  
   *   

   *   
  * *  
 *   * 
*     *
 *   * 
  * *  
   *   

</pre>
<P>
<HR>
After testing thoroughly (<i>especially the set of alerts generated when <u>any</u> of the preconditions are violated</i>), submit this file to its D2L Dropbox.
